    <body>
      <div xml:id="NA142-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu viṉaimuṟṟi mīḷun (ET: mīḷal uṟun) talaimakaṉ (G1+2: talaivaṉ) tērppākaṟkuc colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what HE, who was returning after the work had been accomplished, said to the charioteer.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA142">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            vāṉikupu corinta vayaṅkupeyaṟ kaṭaināṭ</l>
<l>            pāṇi koṇṭa palkāṉ melluṟi</l>
<l>            ñelikōṟ kalappai yataḷoṭu curukkip</l>
<l>            paṟippuṟat tiṭṭa pāṉoṭai yiṭaiya</l>
<l>            ṉuṇpaḵ ṟuvalai yorutiṟa naṉaippat </l>
<l>            taṇṭukāl vaitta voṭuṅkunilai maṭiviḷi</l>
<l>            ciṟutalait toḻuti yēmārt talkum</l>
<l>            puṟavi ṉatuvē poyyā yāṇa</l>
<l>            ralli lāyiṉum viruntuvari ṉuvakku</l>
<l>            mullai cāṉṟa kaṟpiṉ </l>
<l>            melliyaṟ kuṟumaka ḷuṟaivi ṉūrē.</l>
            </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>It [is] in the woodlands,</l>
<l rend="indent">where the milk-selling shepherd, palm-mat put on [his] back,</l>
<l rend="indent2">folding together with a skin the bag<note place="foot">Or: a <term xml:lang="ta">kalappai</term> which consists of skin.</note> [and] churning-wood,</l>
<l rend="indent2">the many-threaded soft net taken in hand, on the last days</l>
<l rend="indent3">of resplendent raining flown down broken from the clouds,</l>
<l rend="indent">abides<note place="foot">K.P. takes <term xml:lang="ta">toḻuti</term> as subject of <term xml:lang="ta">alkum</term>, which would mean to take <term xml:lang="ta">ēmārttu</term> as as adverb ("securely"?).</note>, securing the multitude of small heads</l>
<l rend="indent2">with [his] cloth(?) sound<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">maṭi viḷi</term> is explained by K.P. as a whistle. A slightly fuller version is found in AN 274.9: <term xml:lang="ta">maṭi viṭu vīḷai</term>, although there too <term xml:lang="ta">maṭi</term> is not quite clear.</note>, in [his] isolated state<note place="foot">Here ET with <term xml:lang="ta">taṉi nilai</term> follows the formulaic parallel attested in AN 274.8, which might be a sort of gloss for <term xml:lang="ta">oṭuṅku</term> in this context: the shepherd's state is confined in the sense that he is solitary, so "isolated" can be a reasonable translation.</note>,</l>
<l rend="indent4">[his] staff put down<note place="foot">For <term xml:lang="ta">taṇṭu kāl</term> see the formulaic parallel in AN 174.8; it might be explained as a sort of <term xml:lang="ta">karmadhāraya</term>: "a staff [that functions] as a leg".</note>,</l>
<l rend="indent3">while the fine many drops wet [him] on one side,</l>
<l>– the village where the soft-natured little woman resides,</l>
<l rend="indent4">with [her] fidelity worthy of jasmine<note place="foot">This makes sense only if read as an allusion (the jasmine as a symbol of (re-)union). Or we have to read a meta-poetic statement (thus T.V.G.): the fidelity worthy of <term xml:lang="ta">mullai tiṇai</term>.</note>,</l>
<l rend="indent">that rejoices<note place="foot">What is the subject of <term xml:lang="ta">nuvakkum</term> - <term xml:lang="ta">ūr</term>, <term xml:lang="ta">makaḷ</term> or <term xml:lang="ta">kaṟpiṉ</term>?</note> when a guest comes, be it even at night,</l>
<l rend="indent4">in unfailing fertility</l>
        </lg>
         </div>
